# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-st-regis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The **1979 oil crisis**, sometimes referred to as the **second oil crisis** (in reference to the 1973 oil crisis), refers to the drop in oil production in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution that led to an energy crisis in 1979.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Although the global oil supply only decreased by approximately four percent, the oil markets' reaction raised the price of crude oil drastically over the next 12 months, more than doubling it to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3), equivalent to $175 per barrel ($1,101/m3) in 2025.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The sudden increase in price was connected with fuel shortages similar to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In 1980, following the onset of the Iran–Iraq War, oil production in Iran fell drastically.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Iraq's oil production also dropped significantly, triggering economic recessions worldwide.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Oil prices did not return to pre-crisis levels until the mid-1980s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Oil prices after 1980 began a steady decline over the next 20 years, except for a brief uptick during the Gulf War, which then reached a 60% fall-off in the 1990s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Mexico, Nigeria, and Venezuela's major oil exporters expanded their production during this time.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The Soviet Union became the largest oil producer in the world, and oil from the North Sea and Alaska flooded the market.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In November 1978, a strike by 37,000 workers at Iran's nationalized oil refineries reduced production from 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) per day to about 1.5 million barrels (240,000 m3).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] By bringing navy personnel into crude oil production operations, the government fixed short-term disruptions and by end of November the output came back to almost normal level.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] On January 16, 1979, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and his wife, Farah Pahlavi, left Iran at the behest of Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar, who sought to calm the situation.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] After the departure of the Shah, Ayatollah Khomeini became the new leader of Iran.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The rise in oil prices benefited a few members of the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC), which made record profits.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Under the new Iranian government, oil exports later resumed but production was inconsistent and at a lower volume, further raising prices.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Mana Al Otaiba, increased production to offset most of the decline, and by early 1979 the overall loss in worldwide production was roughly four percent.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The war between Iran and Iraq in 1980 caused a further 7 percent drop in worldwide production.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] OPEC production was surpassed by other exporters such as the United States, as OPEC member nations were divided amongst themselves.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Saudi Arabia, a "swing producer", tried to gain back the market share after 1985, increasing production and causing downward pressure on prices, making high-cost oil production facilities less profitable.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The oil crisis had a mixed impact on the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Richard Nixon had imposed price controls on domestic oil as a result of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Since then, gasoline price controls had been repealed, but those on domestic oil remained.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The Jimmy Carter administration began a phased deregulation of oil prices on April 5, 1979, when the average price of crude oil was US$15.85 per barrel ($100/m3).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Starting with the Iranian revolution, the price of crude oil rose to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3) over the next 12 months (its all-time highest real price until March 3, 2008).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Deregulating domestic oil price controls allowed U.S. oil output to rise sharply from the large Prudhoe Bay fields, while oil imports fell sharply.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Although not directly related, the near-disaster at Three Mile Island on March 28, 1979, also increased anxiety about energy policy and availability.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Due to memories of the oil shortage in 1973, motorists soon began panic buying, and long lines appeared at gas stations, as they had six years earlier.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The average vehicle of the time consumed between two and three liters (about 0.5–0.8 gallons) of gasoline an hour while idling, and it was estimated that Americans wasted up to 150,000 barrels (24,000 m3) of oil per day idling their engines in the lines at gas stations.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In 1979, the amount of oil sold in the United States was only 3.5 percent less than the record set for oil sold in 1978.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] A telephone poll of 1,600 American adults conducted by the Associated Press and NBC News and released in early May 1979 found that only 37 percent of Americans thought the energy shortages were real, nine percent were not sure, and 54 percent thought the energy shortages were a hoax.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Many politicians proposed gas rationing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] One such proponent was Harry Hughes, Governor of Maryland, who proposed odd-even rationing (only people with an odd-numbered license plate could purchase gas on an odd-numbered day), as was used during the 1973 Oil Crisis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Several states implemented odd-even gas rationing, including California, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Texas.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Coupons for gasoline rationing were printed but were never actually used during the 1979 crisis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] On July 15, 1979, President Carter outlined his plans to reduce oil imports and improve energy efficiency in his "Crisis of Confidence" speech, sometimes known as the "malaise" speech.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In the speech, Carter encouraged citizens to do what they could to reduce their use of energy.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] He had already installed water tank heating solar panels on the roof of the White House and a wood-burning stove in the living quarters.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The panels were removed in 1986, reportedly for roof maintenance, during the administration of his successor, Ronald Reagan.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] A speech Carter gave in April 1977 argued that the oil crisis was "the moral equivalent of war".
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In November 1979, Iranian revolutionaries seized the American Embassy, and Carter imposed an embargo on Iranian oil.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In January 1980, he issued the Carter Doctrine, declaring: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States".
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Additionally, as part of his administration's efforts at deregulation, Carter proposed removing price controls that had been imposed by the Richard Nixon administration before the 1973 crisis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Carter agreed to remove price controls in phases.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] They were fully dismantled in 1981 under Reagan.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Carter also said he would impose a windfall profit tax on oil companies.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] While the regulated price of domestic oil was kept to $6 a barrel, the world market price was $30.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In 1980, the U.S. government established the Synthetic Fuels Corporation to produce an alternative to imported fossil fuels.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] When the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent between 1978 and 1980, the oil-producing areas of Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska began experiencing an economic boom and population inflows.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] According to a 2019 study, individuals who were between the ages of 15 and 18 during the 1979 oil crisis were substantially less likely to use cars once they were in their mid-30s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] In response to the high oil prices of the 1970s, industrial nations took steps to reduce their dependence on the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC) oil.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Electric utilities worldwide switched from oil to coal, natural gas, or nuclear power.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] National governments initiated multibillion-dollar research programs to develop alternatives to oil and commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] By 1986, daily worldwide demand for oil dropped by 5 million barrels but, non-OPEC production rose by an even-larger amount.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Consequently, OPEC's market share reduced from 50 percent in 1979 to 29 percent in 1985.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] At the time, Detroit's "Big Three" automakers (Ford, Chrysler, GM) were marketing downsized full-sized automobiles like the Chevrolet Caprice, the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and the Dodge St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Regis which met the CAFE fuel economy mandates passed in 1978.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Detroit's response to the growing popularity of imported compacts like the Toyota Corolla and the Volkswagen Rabbit was the Chevrolet Citation and the Ford Fairmont.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Ford replaced the Ford Pinto with the Ford Escort and Chrysler, on the verge of bankruptcy, introduced the Dodge Aries K.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] GM was having unfavorable market reactions to the Citation and introduced the Chevrolet Corsica and Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 which sold better.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] GM also replaced the Chevrolet Monza, introducing the 1982 Chevrolet Cavalier which was better received.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Ford experienced a similar market rejection of the Fairmont and introduced the front-wheel-drive Ford Tempo in 1984.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Detroit was not well prepared for the sudden rise in fuel prices, and imported brands, primarily the Asian models, which were mass-marketed and had a lower manufacturing cost as opposed to British and West German brands.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] A year after the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Japanese exports later displaced the automotive market once dominated by lower-tier European manufacturers (Renault, Fiat, Opel, Peugeot, MG, Triumph, Citroen).
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Triumph, Simca) or withdraw from the U.S. market, especially in the wake of grey market automobiles or the inability of the vehicle to meet DOT requirements, from emission requirements to automotive lighting.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] Many imported brands utilized fuel-saving technologies such as fuel injection and multi-valve engines over the common use of carburetors.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] The overall fuel economy of cars in the United States increased from about 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) in 1979 to 18 mpg‑US (13 L/100 km; 22 mpg‑imp) by 1985 and 20 mpg‑US (12 L/100 km; 24 mpg‑imp) by 1990.
[src:dodge-st-regis/1979-energy-crisis] This was one factor leading to the subsequent 1980s oil glut.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The **Cadillac Fleetwood Brougham** is a luxury car manufactured by Cadillac from 1977 through 1986.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1987, the Fleetwood Brougham name was shortened to simply Brougham, with production continuing through 1992 with only minor updates.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Cadillac used the "Fleetwood" name as a prefix between 1934 and 1976 on several of its most expensive models, always designating an elevated level of luxury.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] From 1957 until 1961, Cadillac used the "Brougham" sub-designation for its exclusive four-door Eldorado models.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1965, the "Brougham" name was first affixed to "Fleetwood" on the Fleetwood Sixty Special as an upgraded option package, which included a vinyl roof and special "Brougham" script lettering on the sides, but it was not a separate model.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1966, the Fleetwood Brougham was added as a separate model, accompanying the Fleetwood 60 Special, which continued through 1970.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1971, with the Fleetwood Brougham outselling the Fleetwood 60 Special by a large margin, the two models were consolidated into a single model, the Fleetwood 60 Special Brougham, and would continue with this name through 1976.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The car's name was shortened to Fleetwood Brougham with the 1977 downsizing across the GM car line.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The "d'Elegance" and "Talisman" sub-models were also sometimes used to designate upgraded option packages.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Fisher was the Fisher brother most closely involved with Cadillac in its early years.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1916, he joined the Fisher Body Company, which had been formed by two of his brothers in 1908.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Larry (as people knew him) was one of four of the seven Fisher brothers who brought Fisher Body Corporation under the General Motors umbrella in 1919.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Sloan, then the head of General Motors, appointed Fisher as Cadillac General Manager, an office he retained through 1934.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Fisher immediately went to work adding exclusive, custom bodies to the Cadillac range.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Thus he oversaw the purchase of the Fleetwood Metal Body Company by the Fisher Body Corporation in September 1925.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The Fleetwood Body Company of Fleetwood, Pennsylvania, was founded by Harry Urich in the nineteenth century.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] It began as a small community of craftsmen founded by Henry Fleetwood, Esq. of Penwortham, near Lancaster, England (the Fleetwood family flourished in England in the 17th and 18th centuries).
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The rich traditions of 300 years of coach-building that the Fleetwood Body Company applied to its work on cars secured for it a high reputation in automobile circles worldwide by the 1920s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Coachwork was built by Fleetwood for a variety of luxury makes through 1924.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] However, after the Fisher Body Corporation purchased the Fleetwood Body Company in 1925, Fleetwood bodies were reserved exclusively for Cadillac.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] By 1929 GM had purchased the remaining stock holdings of the Fisher Body Corporation and thus became sole owner of both the Fisher and Fleetwood companies.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Originally an enclosed carriage, drawn by a single horse, for 2–4 persons, “Brougham” owes its name to British statesman, Henry Brougham.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Cadillac first used the name in 1916 to designate an enclosed 5-7 passenger sedan body style.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In the thirties, the name was given to a formal body style with open chauffeur compartment and enclosed rear quarters, metal roof and often "razor-edged" styling.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] When Cadillac started offering Fleetwood bodies on some of its cars in 1925, the Brougham body style was Fleetwood bodied every year with the exception of 1926.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] After 1937 the Brougham name was not applied to any Cadillac for the remainder of the pre-WW II period.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The Brougham name would eventually reappear on the 1955 Cadillac Eldorado Brougham show car which preceded the 4-door Eldorado Brougham hardtops of the 1957 to 1960 model years.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] When production of the Eldorado Brougham was shifted in 1959 from the Cadillac Fleetwood plant in Detroit to Pininfarina in Turin, Italy, only then did it acquire Fleetwood wheel discs and doorsill moldings, presumably because the design work and final touches were still being done by Fleetwood.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The 1960 Eldorado Brougham would be the final iteration.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] After a five year absence the Brougham name once again reappeared as an option package on the 1965 Cadillac Sixty Special.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The following year the Brougham moved up to becoming a subseries of the Fleetwood Sixty Special.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Starting in 1971 the Sixty Special was only available as the well equipped Fleetwood Sixty Special Brougham.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] When the Sixty Special Series was retired in 1977, the Fleetwood Brougham took its place as Cadillac's largest owner-driven sedan model through 1986.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] For 1977, GM significantly downsized their full sized cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The DeVille and Fleetwood Brougham rode on the same 121.5" wheelbase and were powered by the 425 cubic inch (7.0 L) V8.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] This engine was basically a de-bored version of the 472/500 (7.7 L/8.2 L) V8 of previous years.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Compared with the 1976 Fleetwood Sixty Special Brougham, the Fleetwood Brougham had a wheelbase 11.5" shorter and weighed nearly 900 lb (400 kg) less.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The new Fleetwood Brougham, which had lost its exclusive longer wheelbase, was now virtually identical to the lesser Sedan de Ville.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Other than the name, there were only subtle exterior differences between a Fleetwood Brougham and Sedan de Ville, including a slightly reshaped B-pillar and rear side windows.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The 1980 refresh eliminated this distinction.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The interior of the Fleetwood was more plush and offered more features as standard.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1980, GM gave all of the full-sized B and C-body line new sheet metal to tidy up the styling and improve aerodynamics.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The basic dashboard design was retained.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Also new for 1980 was a two-door Fleetwood Brougham Coupe, which was based upon the Coupe de Ville but featured an exclusive formal landau vinyl roof.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The 425 cu in (7.0 L) engine, a reduced bore 472, was further debored for 1980-81 to 368 cubic inches or 6.0 liters in order to comply with newly-enacted CAFE standards.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] This engine, called the "V8-6-4", was reliable, but the computer technology of the era was not refined enough for smooth operation and it was dropped from all models but limousines after 1981.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Both the 425 and 368 are small-bore versions of the durable 472 (which was introduced in late 1967 for the '68 model year).
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The larger 500 had the 472's bore but a longer stroke.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] This engine family was the last Cadillac cast-iron engine, and the last 'big-block'.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] During this period, an assortment of engines were offered in the interest of fuel economy.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] These included the Buick 252 V6, diesel Oldsmobile 350 V8, and of Cadillac's own "HT-4100" small block V8, an alloy unit with cast iron cylinder liners which was troublesome and prone to early failure.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The first two were dropped in 1982 once gas prices began falling while the latter persisted through 1986.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] For 1985, Cadillac introduced a brand-new front-wheel drive platform for DeVille and Fleetwood.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] This car featured two "firsts"; it had the first transverse mounted V8 ever (the HT4100) and it was the first car to have a high mounted rear stop-lamp that was federally mandated starting in the 1986 model year.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] The rear wheel drive 1985 Cadillac Fleetwood Brougham continued on nearly unchanged from the 1984 model.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] 1985 was the final model year for the Fleetwood Brougham coupe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] In 1986, the HT-4100 V8 was replaced with an Oldsmobile-sourced 307 cubic inch (5.0 L) V8 in the Fleetwood Brougham.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] For 1987, Cadillac revised its model nomenclature for its premium sedan lines.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] To reduce market confusion over the smaller front-wheel drive Fleetwood (introduced in 1985), the D-body Fleetwood Brougham was renamed the Cadillac Brougham.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] Produced since 1977 with only incremental changes since its 1980 update, the Brougham was offered through 1992.
[src:dodge-st-regis/cadillac-fleetwood-brougham] For 1993, the D-body Cadillac was restyled and rebranded as the Cadillac Fleetwood; the Brougham name also returned, becoming a trim package.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The **California Highway Patrol** (**CHP**) is the principal state police agency for the U.S. state of California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP has primary jurisdiction, including patrol and investigations, over all California freeways and state property.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Additionally, the CHP is responsible for the enforcement of all laws regulating the operation of vehicles on highways, including all roadways, outside incorporated city limits.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP can exercise law enforcement powers anywhere within the state.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The California State Legislature originally established the California Highway Patrol as a branch of the Division of Motor Vehicles in the Department of Public Works, with legislation signed by Governor C.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] It was subsequently established as a separate department with legislation signed by Governor Earl Warren in 1947.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP gradually assumed increased responsibility beyond the enforcement of the State Vehicle Act and eventually absorbed the smaller California State Police in 1995.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] It is currently organized as a department under the California State Transportation Agency (CalSTA).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In addition to its highway patrol duties, the CHP also provides other services including protecting state buildings and facilities (most notably the California State Capitol) and guarding state officials.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP also works with municipal and federal law enforcement agencies, providing assistance in investigations, patrol and other aspects of law enforcement.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The California Highway Patrol is the largest state police agency in the United States, with 11,000 employees, over 7,600 of whom are sworn, according to a study in December 2019.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP gained international recognition in the late 1970s and the early 1980s, through the broadcast of the TV series *CHiPs*, which chronicled the adventures of two fictional CHP motorcycle officers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP is responsible for public safety and law enforcement on all freeways and expressways, throughout the state, regardless of whether the freeway is within the boundaries of an incorporated city.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Additionally, the CHP is responsible for the enforcement of all laws regulating the operation of vehicles, and the use of the highways and public roads in unincorporated portions of a county.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Furthermore, CHP officers act as bailiffs for the California Supreme Court and the six California Courts of Appeal, and also provide security at buildings occupied by the State of California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP officers enforce the California Vehicle Code, pursue fugitives spotted on the highways, and attend to all significant obstructions and crashes within their jurisdiction.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP officers are responsible for investigating and disposing of car accidents, disabled vehicles, debris, and other impediments to the flow of traffic.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] They are often the first responders at the scene of an accident (or obstruction), and in turn summon paramedics, firefighters, tow truck drivers, or Caltrans personnel.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP files traffic crash reports for state highways and within unincorporated areas.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP responds to and investigates all accidents involving school buses throughout the state including incorporated cities.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP also has Multidisciplinary Accident Investigation Teams (MAIT) for the investigation of complex traffic crashes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Officers patrol in various vehicles including the 2014–2021 Ford Police Interceptor Utility, 2016–2023 Dodge Charger, and in 2015 Chevrolet Tahoe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In alternate duties, Officers have been utilizing some police cars from the early 2000s such as Ford Expeditions.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Mobile Road Enforcement (MRE) Officers delegated with enforcing commercial vehicles utilize the 2016 Ford F-250 and 2016–2023 Ram 1500.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP also publishes data on traffic accidents in California from a database called SWITRS (Statewide Integrated Traffic Records System).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] After the September 11, 2001 attacks, the CHP became responsible for securing and patrolling a number of potential terrorist targets in California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These sites include nuclear power plants, government buildings, and key infrastructure sites.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP also maintains a SWAT team on 24‑hour stand‑by to respond to any terrorist activity.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In September 2005, the CHP sent its two Mobile Field Forces (highly trained and equipped quick reaction/deployment teams for civil disturbances and/or disasters) to the Gulf Coast to assist in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Before the National Guard arrived, the CHP had four patrol helicopters over Marianna, Florida, more than eighty vehicles on the ground, and more than 200 officers and other staff, including a SWAT team, deployed in New Orleans.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP also has officers assigned to drug task forces and other criminal investigative task forces throughout the state, and maintains highly trained Warrant Service Teams (WST) throughout each of its Divisions.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These teams serve high-risk felony arrest and search warrants generated as a result of CHP investigations, and the WST assists local, state, and federal law enforcement agencies to serve the same type of high-risk warrants.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP investigators also work closely with agents of the State Bureau of Investigation, Office of the Attorney General.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP also has a Special Response Team (SRT) for rapidly responding to natural disasters or civil disturbances throughout the state.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Specialized training and equipment help to quickly quell unrest, preserve life, prevent property damage, and ensure the safety of the public.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Additionally, the CHP has dozens of narcotic patrol and explosive detection K-9 teams stationed throughout the state.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The California Highway Patrol's additional responsibilities includes a governor protection detail.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Somewhat controversially, the cities of Oakland and Stockton have contracted with the California Highway Patrol to assist their police departments with local patrol duties, including traffic stops and responding to 911 calls.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] By law, salaries are set by an average of the five largest police departments in the state.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2012, the top paid CHP officer received $483,581, 44 other officers earning over $200,000, and over 5,000 officers receiving over $100,000.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2011, CHP officers earned $82.4 million in overtime, triple the amount in the second largest state, and with one officer earning over $93,000 in overtime alone.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Officers are strictly prohibited from working more than 16.5 hours at a time before having to take a minimum eight-hour break.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 1999, Governor Gray Davis signed SB 400, which allowed CHP officers to retire at age 50 and continue receiving as much as 90% of their peak pay as a pension.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] This raised the pension earned for 30 years of service from an average of $62,218 to $96,270.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] New officers have a retirement age of 57 in accordance with CalPers 2.7% at 57 formula.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As of 2019, a new contract was negotiated with the state, causing officers to increase their contribution to the retirement plan by deferring any percentage over 3% of their annual raise towards their pension.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] This brings their contribution closer to a 50–50 split with the state, while boosting state contributions toward the officers' retirements from other sources.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP is led by the Commissioner, who is appointed by the Governor of California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The Deputy Commissioner is also appointed by the Governor and the Assistant Commissioners are appointed by the Commissioner.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On February 3, 2023, Acting Commissioner Duryee was appointed to Commissioner by Governor Gavin Newsom.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2010 the CHP received initial accreditation by the Commission on Accreditation for Law Enforcement Agencies (CALEA).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Upon receiving this honor, the CHP became the largest CALEA-accredited law enforcement agency in the nation.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On November 16, 2013, the CHP Academy was formally recognized as an accredited Public Safety Training Academy by CALEA, becoming the first accredited state police training academy in the nation.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Additionally, the department succeeded in its bid for Advanced Law Enforcement reaccreditation, and remains the largest accredited law enforcement agency in the nation.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On November 22, 2014, the CHP communications centers were formally accredited by CALEA under the Public Safety Communications Agencies Accreditation Program.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Having received this honor, the CHP became the first accredited state highway patrol in the nation to receive communications accreditation.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP is one of nearly 20 agencies to have received this award.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Since its inception in 1929, 233 officers have died in the line of duty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The top three frequent causes of line of duty deaths to date are (in order of cause): Automobile/Motorcycle Accidents, Gunfire, and Vehicular Assault (i.e., struck by drunk driver, reckless driving, or hearing and/or visually impaired drivers).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] 1964 was the deadliest year, in which eight officers died in the line of duty; 1970 and 1978 were the second deadliest years, in which seven officers died in the line of duty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The Mexico Liaison Unit is a Border Division Unit based in San Diego.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Since the CHP has no direct jurisdiction in Mexico, officers from the Unit work closely with Mexican authorities to recover and find stolen vehicles and assist with other law enforcement issues.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The unit was originally established in 1958 and consisted of only one officer.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] It was discontinued in the 1970s, and reestablished in 1980.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The unit now consists of one sergeant and six officers, all of whom are fluent in Spanish.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On April 6, 1970, four California Highway Patrol officers were killed in a 41⁄2‑minute shootout in the Newhall region of Southern California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The incident is a landmark in CHP history because of both its emotional impact and the procedural and doctrinal reforms implemented by the CHP in the incident's aftermath.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The shootout occurred in a restaurant parking lot just before midnight.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Officers Walt Frago and Roger Gore were alerted by radio of a vehicle carrying someone who brandished a weapon.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] They spotted the car, fell in behind, called for backup, and began the stop procedure.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] When the suspects' vehicle came to a halt in the parking lot, the driver was instructed to step out of the vehicle and spread his hands on the hood.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Gore approached him and Frago moved to the passenger side.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The passenger side door suddenly swung open and the passenger sprung out, firing at Frago, who fell with two shots in his chest.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The gunman, later identified as Jack Twinning, then turned and fired once at Gore, who returned fire.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In that moment the driver, Bobby Davis, turned and shot Gore twice at close range.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] When Officers James Pence and George Alleyn drove in moments later, they could not see suspects or other officers, but both immediately came under fire.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Officer Pence put out an 11‑99 call ("officer in distress") then took cover behind the passenger door.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Alleyn grabbed his shotgun, and positioned himself behind the driver-side door.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Both officers were mortally wounded in the ensuing exchange, and one suspect was hit.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Suspects Jack Twinning and Bobby Davis escaped, later abandoned their vehicle and then split up.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] For nine hours, officers blanketed the area searching for the killers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Twinning broke into a house and briefly held a man hostage.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Officers used tear gas before storming the house, but Twinning committed suicide with the shotgun he stole from Frago.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Davis was captured, stood trial and convicted on four counts of murder.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] He was sentenced to death, but in 1972, the California Supreme Court declared the death penalty to be cruel and unusual punishment and in 1973, the court commuted his sentence to life in prison.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] A follow-up investigation eventually led to a complete revision of procedures during high-risk and felony stops.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Firearms procedures have also changed fundamentally due to this incident, and physical methods of arrest have been improved.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The police baton and pepper spray have been added to the officer's arsenal, with more in‑depth training in their use.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The 25th anniversary of the Newhall Incident was observed on April 6, 1995, at the present Newhall Area office, where a brick memorial pays tribute to Officers George Alleyn (6290), Walt Frago (6520), Roger Gore (6547) and James Pence (6885).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The memorial once stood at the former Newhall office, but was rebuilt at the new site, about one mile (1.6 km) from the scene of the slayings.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On July 12, 1995, the California State Police, which was a separate agency, was absorbed into the CHP, thus greatly expanding the agency's mandate.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In addition to safety on the state highway system, it is now responsible for the safety of all elected state officials and all people who work in or are utilizing a state building in California, such as the State Capitol Building in Sacramento.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] It has also been discussed to merge the Law Enforcement Division of the California Department of Fish and Wildlife into the California Highway Patrol.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] By doing so, this may allow for better protection of California's environment and natural resources.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The California Highway Patrol currently issues the Smith & Wesson M&P pistol chambered in .40 S&W, replacing the Smith & Wesson Model 4006 TSW.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On Thursday the 7th of May 2026, Smith and Wesson announced via their Instagram that The California Highway Patrol had selected the M&P9 M2.0 to replace the M&P40.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] When motor vehicles in California were first seen as needing legislation, law enforcement agencies began to patrol using motorcycles, cars and trucks.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Motorcycle officers in 1920 Fresno, started a group to assist each other and promote road safety – the Joaquin Valley Traffic Officer's Association – led by Harry Wilson who they elected as president.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] They renamed themselves the California Association of Highway Patrolmen in 1921, and became the California Highway Patrol in 1927 under the auspices of the Department of Motor Vehicles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As of 2023, CHP had transitioned to BMW motorcycles with the BMW R1250RT-P to replace the aging fleet of Harley-Davidsons.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Through the public competitive bidding process, the Harley-Davidson Electraglide motorcycle was selected as the primary enforcement motorcycle for the California Highway Patrol in 2013.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These replacement enforcement motorcycles will replenish the department's aging motorcycle fleet.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In a cost-saving move, the CHP previously deferred the purchase of replacement motorcycles and has not purchased enforcement motorcycles since January 14, 2011.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As a result, approximately 20 percent of the current fleet has logged 100,000 plus miles – well exceeding the manufacturer's warranty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP's motorcycle program enhances public safety.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Motorcycle officers are able to effectively enforce traffic laws in areas in which enforcement by four-wheel vehicles is impractical.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Motorcycles can access scenes of accidents and natural disasters more quickly and work commute traffic in way that is unique to the motorcycle.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Additionally, motorcycles play a special role in dignitary protection.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP has approximately 415 enforcement motorcycles working the roads throughout California.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP purchased 121 of the Harley-Davidson enforcement motorcycles to replace motorcycles that have high mileage or have been damaged in traffic collisions.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As of June 2013, approximately 22 percent of the CHP's motorcycle fleet is over 100,000 miles with more than half of those over 125,000 miles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] On average, a CHP enforcement motorcycle is driven 14,000 miles per year.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Early motorcycles used included Indian, Harley-Davidson and Henderson manufactured bikes during the 1920s and 30s; though by 1941, the main manufacturers used at the training academy were Harley-Davidson and Indian.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 1998, CHP began using the BMW R1100RT-P, with features including a helmet interface for communications, two batteries, and a top speed of 130 miles per hour (210 km/h).
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The Department of General Services is responsible for selecting a vehicle based on price, performance and payload capacity for the CHP.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The bid specifications require a pursuit-rated, rear-wheel drive or all-wheel drive that can carry at least 1,500 pounds, the approximate weight of four officers, their equipment, and the police vehicle equipment.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor averaged 14 mpg city and 21 mpg highway.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The new Ford Police Interceptor Utility Vehicle costs $26,578, which includes a 5-year, 100,000-mile warranty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The department was paying $24,043 for the Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptors and recently spent hundreds of thousands of dollars per month to maintain all vehicles no longer covered by warranty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Several vehicles were allocated to public affairs officers and are used for recruiting purposes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] An example of these vehicles can be seen at the California State Fair and other venues.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The last Crown Victoria's were retired in September 2020.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP also uses the Ford F-250, RAM 2500, and Chevrolet Silverado 1500 (still in testing) for commercial vehicle enforcement.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In July 2016, it was announced that the CHP would be taking delivery of 516 2016 Dodge Charger Pursuits equipped with the 3.6L Pentastar V6 in RWD configuration.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These cars were hoped to be more reliable than the Ford Police Interceptor Utility, which have been plagued with various recalls and breakdowns, the most notable breakdowns being transmission and PTU (transfer case) failures.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2017, it was announced that the CHP were going to start using Chevrolet Tahoe Police Pursuit Vehicles (PPV) for rural and resident posts, along with areas that see snowfall in the winter months.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] This is because of their ability to carry a larger "basic load" of normal issue equipment, equipment that may be only in a few cars, and/or not carried in patrol cars at all, in a more urban setting, along with the selectable 4 wheel drive system to allow better performance in the snow.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2022, CHP began rolling out an all wheel drive version of the 2020 Charger Pursuit.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These, like their predecessor, are powered by the naturally aspirated 3.6L Pentastar V6 engine, making 292bhp and 260lb/ft of torque.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2025, CHP Fleet Operations rolled out a limited number of 2020 Charger Pursuit in 5.7L Hemi V8 in a rear-wheel drive configuration, making 370bhp and 395lb/ft of torque, outfitted with license plate readers (LPRs), to deplete the remaining stock of Chargers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As of 2023 the California Highway Patrol has officially rolled out its 299 2020 Ford Police Interceptor Utility after a 3-year hold due to an issue involving the RF interference from the headlights to the department's VHF-Lowband radios.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These vehicles are powered by the naturally aspirated flex fuel 3.3L V6, making 285bhp and 260lb/ft of torque.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] During 2023, the average mileage of its in-service primary patrol vehicles ranged anywhere from 150,000 miles to nearly 400,000 miles, proving the 2013-2019 Year Interceptor Utilities nearly or just as capable as the previous Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptors.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] It was also reported in 2023 that the CHP is testing the latest generation Dodge Durango special service package, and has selected the 2020 Chevrolet Tahoe PPV to be upfitted and utilized after completing the latest batch of Dodge Chargers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2024 the California Highway Patrol Fleet Operations rolled out 400 2024 Dodge Durangos with 5.7L Hemi V8 engines in all wheel drive configuration, making 360bhp and 390lb/ft of torque.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] All of these Durangos are outfitted with “360-degree concealed” lighting systems, making them harder to detect until their lights turn on.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] As it stands, the highest mileage vehicle that was used by the California Highway Patrol was a 2013 Ford Explorer PIU, with an odometer at 384,857 miles upon retirement, which had patrolled the California/Nevada Border in Needles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP utilizes both helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] George Michael Gwaltney, a former officer from Barstow, was convicted on May 10, 1984, in federal court for the on-duty rape and murder of 23-year-old Robin Bishop on January 11, 1982.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] He had reported finding a dead body off a deserted stretch of Interstate 15 the same day he murdered her with his service weapon.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Gwaltney was tried twice for this murder at the San Bernardino County Court House.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The first trial ended with the jury deadlocked 8–4 and the second 7–5.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The district attorney attempted to try Gwaltney a third time, but a Superior Court judge dismissed the murder charge.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Since Gwaltney was not convicted in the first two state trials, the FBI took over the case.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The FBI was able to piece together the events leading up to the on-duty rape and murder of Robin Bishop and interrogating Gwaltney's alibi, Preston Olson and his mother.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] There was more forensic evidence that the FBI succeeded in getting to build their case against Gwaltney: soon his story started to fall apart.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] After the six-month investigation by the FBI, Gwaltney was arrested in Barstow and tried at the US District Court in Los Angeles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] He was represented by a public defender who chose not to have Gwaltney testify as he had done in the previous two state trials.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] He was found guilty of the murder, rape and the deprivation of Robin Bishop's civil rights while on duty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] He was the first California Highway Patrol officer to be charged with the indictment of violating the civil rights of Robin Bishop as well as being the first CHP officer known to commit a murder while on duty.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Following the convictions, Gwaltney was sentenced to 90 years in prison, with eligiblity for parole after 30 years: he died in federal custody in 1997 of a heart attack.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Craig Peyer, a former officer from Poway, is serving a twenty-five year to life prison sentence for the on-duty strangulation and murder of 20-year-old Cara Knott on December 27, 1986.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] After she was killed, Knott's body was discarded over an abandoned highway bridge.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Peyer was convicted of first-degree murder in 1988.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Though he has maintained innocence ever since, Peyer has been denied parole consistently.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2004, the parole board offered Peyer the chance to prove his alleged innocence by providing a DNA sample to compare against a drop of blood found on Cara's shoe, using modern DNA profiling.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Peyer declined to provide a sample, nor explain why he declined to do so.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] In 2006, two officers forwarded photos taken of Nikki Catsouras, a teenager who died in a motor vehicle accident, to colleagues without authorization.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These photos quickly spread on the internet.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The family sued and reached a settlement in the case with CHP for $2.37 million in 2012.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP hosts or partners with numerous programs for public safety education and community involvement.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] When the CHP was formed, there were discussions as to what to call this new agency.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The consensus was for the name "California Highway Patrol".
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The American Automobile Association (AAA) is a private organization which provided, among other things, roadside assistance to their members.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] At that time, the AAA had a fleet of trucks which patrolled the roads so they could assist their members.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] These trucks carried a sign which said "Highway Patrol".
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP organizers decided it would be best to contact the AAA to see if they would object to the state using this name.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The AAA considered the idea, and gave their consent.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Jack Holt played the titular hero, a rookie CHP officer, in the 1936 film *Crash Donovan*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] CHP personnel acted as technical advisors to the 1950s TV show *Highway Patrol*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] "Roadblock" was a presentation of the anthology TV series *Studio 57*, in which Mike Connors played a CHP motorcycle officer trying to track down a gang of armed robbers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Meant as a pilot, it never became a series.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] MacDonald's short story "The Homesick Buick," which was originally published in *Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] The CHP gained international recognition in the late 1970s to the early 1980s through the broadcast of the TV series *CHiPs*, which chronicled the adventures of two fictional CHP motorcycle officers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] "Chippy" is sometimes used in California English as a colloquialism for officers, analogous to "State-y" elsewhere.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Retired CHP Assistant Chief Kevin Mince, writing as "K.T.
[src:dodge-st-regis/california-highway-patrol] Mince", has written three novels featuring Erin "Red" Wolff, a lesbian CHP officer, who rises from sergeant to captain in the course of the trilogy.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:dodge-st-regis/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis** is a full-size automobile which was manufactured by the Chrysler Corporation from 1978 to 1981 and marketed by Dodge from the 1979 to 1981 model years.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was the largest Dodge sedan, positioned above the mid-size Diplomat and Aspen.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] In contrast to both the Monaco and the Diplomat, the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was offered solely as a four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] With a production run of three model years over a single generation, the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis is one of the shortest-lived Dodge nameplates.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Deriving its name from a 1950s Chrysler trim package, the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was the first example of downsizing of the full-size Dodge sedan line.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1982, the model line was discontinued, with the Dodge Diplomat serving as the largest Dodge; the next full-size Dodge sedan was the 1990 Dodge Monaco (derived from the Eagle Premier, itself a version of the Renault 25).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Dodge would not market a rear-wheel drive sedan until the 2006 Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was assembled alongside the Chrysler Newport, Chrysler New Yorker, and Plymouth Gran Fury by Chrysler at Lynch Road Assembly (Detroit, Michigan), becoming the final production vehicles produced at the facility.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] In total, 64,502 examples were produced.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was based on the rear wheel drive Chrysler R-body platform.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] As Chrysler needed to expedite a downsized replacement for the 1974–1977 C-body to market (in response to the 1973 oil crisis), the R-body was developed from existing underpinnings at minimal costs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] In place of redesigning the full-size C-body, Chrysler developed the R-body as an update of the intermediate B-body (last released in 1971, dating to 1962).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Used by a wide variety of Chrysler model lines, the B-body architecture underpinned model lines ranging from the Dodge Coronet and Plymouth Belvedere to the Dodge Charger and Chrysler Cordoba.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Compared to its 1977 Dodge Royal Monaco predecessor, the Dodge St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis shed 5.5 inches in length, 2.7 inches in width, 3 inches in wheelbase, and nearly 900 pounds of curb weight (dependent on powertrain).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The 225 Slant-6 inline-6 was now the standard engine with optional 318 and 360 V8s; a three-speed automatic was paired to all three engines.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] In deference to fuel economy standards, the 400 and 440 big-block V8s were deleted from the engine lineup.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The front suspension continued to feature Chrysler's longitudinal front torsion bars, called Torsion-Aire, with an anti-sway bar, and a solid rear axle connected to leaf springs.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis" name first saw use as an uplevel trim package on the 1956 New Yorker hardtop coupe and again on the 1974–78 Chrysler New Yorker Brougham coupe.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Offered only as a four-door notchback sedan, the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was styled with frameless door glass (the rear quarter glass was fixed).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] To further distinguish the model line from its Plymouth Gran Fury, Chrysler Newport, and Chrysler New Yorker counterparts, the front fascia was styled with transparent retractable headlamp covers (introduced on the 1978 Dodge Magnum).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The Chrysler R-body cars (like their 1974–78 predecessors) arrived at precisely the wrong time, as a second gasoline crisis hit the U.S. in 1979.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] In contrast to the clean-sheet Ford and GM designs, the dire financial situation of Chrysler relegated the company to retool an existing chassis.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] While shifting to an intermediate chassis allowed the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis a smaller exterior footprint over the 1974-1977 Monaco, it remained far larger than its Ford LTD and Chevrolet Caprice competitors (at 220.2 inches long, an inch shorter than a Cadillac Fleetwood Brougham).
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Coinciding with the 1979 fuel crisis, high interest rates and the uncertain future of the company forced Chrysler into a high proportion of fleet sales for its full-size sedans.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Despite being an introductory model, nearly 30% of St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis production was dedicated for police/law enforcement use.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1979, Chrysler withdrew Plymouth entirely from the full-size segment (making the Volare the largest Plymouth that year); for 1980, a R-body Gran Fury was reinstated, nearly exclusively for fleet sales.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The Chrysler R platform was dropped during the middle of the 1981 model year, with the Dodge St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis ending its product run; to reduce model overlap, Chrysler ended sales of the Newport.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1982, Dodge began marketing the Diplomat as its largest four-door sedan; nearly 16 inches shorter than the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis, the mid-size Diplomat was the final rear-wheel drive sedan marketed by Dodge during the 1980s.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1990, the Dodge brand re-entered the full-size segment with the fifth-generation Dodge Monaco.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] A rebranded version of the Eagle Premier (adapted from the Renault 25), the 1990 Monaco was the first version produced with front-wheel drive, slotted above the Dodge Dynasty in size.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1993, Dodge introduced its first Chrysler-developed full-size sedan with front-wheel drive, the Dodge Intrepid.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] While closer in exterior size to the Diplomat, the Intrepid nearly matches the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Following its introduction, the Dodge St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis saw heavy use as a police car in the United States.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Outside of California, a 195-hp 360 V8 engine was available as part of the A38 Police Package; the option package was popular by law enforcement of the time.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was fitted with a 190 hp (140 kW) four-bbl 360 V8.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] For 1980, the 360 was replaced by a 155 hp (116 kW) 318 V8 4-bbl with California emissions to comply with state emissions regulations; specification sheets provided by Dodge for these cars omitted references to low rates of acceleration and top speed.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The California Highway Patrol (CHP) was a major purchaser of the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis, taking delivery of 900 for $7,091 (equivalent to $27,708 in 2025) each with 318 V8 powertrains.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] The changed powertrain proved unpopular with the CHP, as the top speed of the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis was reduced to 85 mph (137 km/h), or 65 mph (105 km/h) while ascending a hill.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Nicknamed 'dog cars' by officers, the CHP approved efforts to remove the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis from their fleet at a meeting of California's Little Hoover Commission in October 1980, selling 86, some of which had yet to enter service, by the end of the year for the same price they were purchased, and replacing them with Chevrolets.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Coinciding with its usage in law enforcement, the St.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] Regis appeared on multiple 1980s police-based television series, including *Sledge Hammer!*, *The A-Team* , "CHiPs", and *T.J.
[src:dodge-st-regis/dodge-st-regis] With the low number built (in comparison to its Ford and Chevrolet competitors) and the high percentage destroyed in film and TV work or retired after police use, very few examples survive today.
